ce:section.ce:para:
The photocatalytic decomposition of RhB dye was investigated employing the synthesized samples i.e., N-C-dots, SgCN/ZnO, and N-C-dots/SgCN/ZnO. 0.05 g of each sample is used for photocatalytic elimination of 50 mL of RhB dye at 10 ppm concentration. The absorption peak's intensity at 554 nm decreased with time (0–75 min), indicating a drop in dye content. It was observed that all of the synthesized samples displayed little adsorption under dark conditions. However, as shown in Fig. 9
                        , N-C-dots/SgCN/ZnO exhibited the highest photocatalytic dye decontamination, degrading 82.89 % RhB dye in 75 min [Table 2
                        ]. The most plausible explanation is that the incorporation of C-dots lowered the electron-hole reintegration probability by function as electrons acceptor and consequently improved the composite's photocatalytic performance over its individual components. In addition, the presence of various surface functional groups on N-C-dots facilitated the adsorption of greater number of RhB dye molecules on N-C-dots/SgCN/ZnO through various interactions such as H-bonding. The adsorption of greater number of RhB dye molecules on N-C-dots/SgCN/ZnO surface led to greater degree of RhB dye degradation. As a result, further studies have been conducted using N-C-dots/SgCN/ZnO.

Because gCN and ZnO both are semiconductors UV-light active photocatalyst with band gaps of roughly 3.2 and 2.9 eV, sequentially. Electron-hole pairs are created when an electron from the VB moves to the CB under the influence of UV light. The electron in the SgCN CB migrates to the ZnO CB due to band positions of ZnO and SgCN, whereas the hole at the ZnO VB moves to the SgCN VB [64]. By lowering the rate at which electron-hole couples recombine, this will raise the total photocatalytic efficacy. As already stated, N-C-dots have negligible participation in photocatalytic eradication of dye, but they play two major roles in the ternary composite: 1) they may aid in capturing electrons through preventing the reintegration of e−-h+ couples of SgCN and ZnO and promote the faster transport of e− and h+ for photocatalytic reactions, 2) surface functional moieties of N-C-dots, such as -OH, -CONH2, -COH, etc. can enable dye molecules' adsorption photocatalyst's surface via H-bond attachments to RhB dye molecules, that is a key step for photocatalytic elimination of dye [8]. Therefore, the production of highly photoreactive radicals like •OH and O2
                        • − radicals, is aided by photo-induced e−/h+ couple. A typical chemical pathway which take place in course of photocatalytic degradation of dye by the resulting composite has been depicted in Eqs. 7–20 (Fig. 15
                        ) [65–67]. In addition, the possible intermediate during photocatalytic RhB dye degradation has been depicted in Fig. S1 (Supplementary File) [68].
